"mk19_bb_gm_s77_inline_t1"
],
"forceOpen":true
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"b516f6",
"children":[
"There are several subtypes of melanoma:"
]
},
{
"type":"list",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"777ed6",
"children":[
"Lentigo maligna begins as a uniformly pigmented, light brown patch on the face or upper trunk that is confined to the epidermis and resembles a solar lentigo. Over time, the lesion expands and becomes more variegated in color."
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"c1a91d",
"children":[
"Superficial spreading melanoma presents as a well-defined asymmetric patch or plaque with an irregular border, variation in color, and an expanding diameter. This type tends to occur on the back in men and the legs in women (areas that receive intermittent sun and are prone to sunburn)."
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"a66c2d",
"children":[
"Nodular melanomas are the most aggressive form (invading deeper structures); they are responsible for most deaths from melanoma."
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"5748ce",
"children":[
"Acral lentiginous melanomas are the most common type of melanoma seen in patients with dark skin."
]
},
" "
]
},
{
"type":"inline-wrap",
"wrapId":"2",
"contentIds":[
"mk19_bb_gm_f44"
],
"forceOpen":true
